<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n19017d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n19" href="#n19017d">N19 (VI.B.19)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n19all.htm#n19017d"> 17(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> horrified at <font face="wake">C</font>&apos;s / credulity</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Two other boys were reported to me as having made the same judgement &hellip; when they were allowed to satisy their curiosity and look at their baby sister&apos;s body for the first time <font color="green">[&ldquo;But her widdler&apos;s quite small &hellip; When she grows up it&apos;ll get bigger all right&rdquo;]</font>. One might well feel <mark>horrified at</mark> such signs of a premature ruin of a child&apos;s intellect. Why did not these young inquirers state what they really saw, namely that there was no widdler there? <small> Sigmund Freud, <a name="SFLH" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SFLH"><cite title="source">&ldquo;Analysis of a Phobia in a Five-Year old boy&rdquo; (&lsquo;Little Hans&rsquo;)&rdquo;</cite></a> (May 1925) 155n [on the subject of girls lacking a penis]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
